ce:section.ce:para:
The adsorption kinetics of meropenem onto the N-GQDs@MIP were investigated by analyzing the time-dependent fluorescence quenching response. Experimental data were fitted to various kinetic models, including pseudo-first-order, pseudo-second-order, and intraparticle diffusion models. The results revealed that the adsorption kinetics followed a pseudo-second-order kinetic model, with an R2 value of 0.996. This suggests that the rate-limiting step is a chemical adsorption process involving valence forces through the sharing or exchange of electrons between meropenem and the N-GQDs@MIP. The equilibrium adsorption capacity (q

                           e
                        ) was calculated to be 1.860 μg/mg, and the rate constant (k

                           2
                        ) was determined to be 0.0028 mg/μg·min. These kinetic data confirm the efficient binding of meropenem to the imprinted cavities and the fast-binding kinetics.

The analytical performance of the developed N-GQDs@MIP sensor was evaluated under optimized conditions, where increasing concentrations of meropenem resulted in a linear quenching of the fluorescence intensity (Fig. 6
                        A). The sensor exhibited a strong linear response in the range of 25–1500 ng/mL, with a correlation coefficient (r2) of 0.9994, indicating excellent linearity (Fig. 6B). The LOD and LOQ were calculated to be 7.42 ng/mL and 22.48 ng/mL, respectively, based on the residual standard deviation of the regression line and the slope (Table 3
                        ). These values demonstrate the sensor's high sensitivity and suitability for detecting trace levels of meropenem in complex matrices.
